There is a heavy military and police presence in what the government officials have dubbed coronavirus “hotspots”. As I drove on the N1 from Pretoria to Johannesburg, to a large extent the streets were devoid of people. The police and soldiers were there as I passed Soweto. It has been said if residents will not, of their own accord, remain indoors, the heavy-handed military will keep them there. If they dare to stray outside, gather to pray or even to ply their trade as vendors, the soldiers will put a stop to it. While the nation decries measures employed by...